    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <dateline>April 12<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1773.</dateline>
                <opener>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I am now on the point of leaving Town but just steal a moment to say that
                    everything in <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0028">the
                        genera</title>
                    </bibl> was quite agreable except what I hinted: Pray let me
                    know when the whole of y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> timid impression is sold
                    that I may return you a corrected copy for a 2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. I
                    shall rob you of no more copies, but buy of you what I want to give away. The
                    books you desire <sic>will given</sic> to y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> friend
                    by <persName ref="pe0026">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                        White</persName>. you shall have the <rs type="art" ref="ar0112">set of
                        prints </rs>you desire when the book is published</p>
                <p>Pray give me the history of <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bidb.xml#bi0074">the poetical Bible at Glasgow</title>
                    </bibl>, &amp; some capital
                    quotations from it. I missed <persName ref="pe0036">Ld Breadalbane</persName>
                    which I regret. Much talk of war: an unhappy affair. I beg you w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> direct your next to <placeName ref="pl0702">Flintshire</placeName>.</p>
                <closer>adieu <salute>truely yrs</salute>
                    <signed>
                        <persName ref="pe0232">T Pennant</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>I print in q<hi rend="superscript">to</hi> for sake of the fine plates &amp;
                        employ <persName ref="pe0141">Major</persName>, <persName ref="pe0142">Canor</persName>, <persName ref="pe0143">Mazel</persName> &amp;
                            <persName ref="pe0144">Lerpiniere</persName> all capital hands.</p>
                    <p>Oblige me with the history of <bibl type="authorial">
                            <title ref="bidb.xml#bi0074">Zachary Boyds Bible</title>
                        </bibl> &amp; also
                        the most capital verses. also the verses or <bibl type="authorial">
                            <title ref="bi0586">epitaph on the old woman saw so many
                            reigns</title>
                        </bibl>.<note type="editorial">A reference to the epitaph
                            of Marjory Scot (or Scott) of <placeName ref="pl0099">Dunkeld</placeName>, who reputedly died in 1728, having lived for a
                            century and seen out the reigns of eight Scottish kings. The epitaph,
                            which Pennant attributes to one Alexander Pennicuik, is a patriotic
                            lament for the end of Scottish independence and Stuart rule, and is
                            printed in the <bibl type="editorial">
                                <title ref="bi0010">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Tour in Scotland 1772 Part II</hi>
                                </title>
                                (London: 1776), p.66.</bibl>
                        </note>
                    </p>
                </postscript>

            </div>
            <div>
